Association of North America, as well as other groups that

42
00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:34.140
focus on cancer. But this is not an uncommon thing.

43
00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:37.960
Losing or changes in smell and taste, it's something that

44
00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:41.840
it's a daily reminder that there's a cancer diagnosis in your

45
00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:42.220
body.

46
00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.640
That was not what was supposed to happen. Let's go here.

47
00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:49.980
For some people, their daily coffee when they start the morning doesn't taste as

48
00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.560
much as it used to be, and it doesn't even smell like that.

49
00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:57.340
For some people, even brushing your teeth, it's kind of a

50
00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:01.210
trip to a dumpster. There are distortions that are particularly

51
00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.860
nauseating, and really remember the smell of trash or

52
00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:06.600
excrements.

53
00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:11.310
Even if you don't have active nausea, actually, thinking

54
00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:15.420
about sharing a meal with family and friends becomes something that it's

55
00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:19.500
prohibitive. And also, you might be experiencing

56
00:03:19.660 --> 00:03:22.540
some metal mouth or strong bitter

57
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:27.520
experiences in your mouth. And again, this becomes a painful daily

58
00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:31.320
reminder that life is not like it used to be, and this is quite

59
00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:32.120
disruptive.

60
00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:37.420
So chemosensory health, it's not a nice-to-have.

61
00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:38.260
It actually

62
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:43.120
is underlying a lot of behaviors that are related

63
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:43.920
to survival.

64
00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:48.020
We use our smell definitely to drive ourselves to food.

65
00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:50.560
We use our taste to drive consumption.

66
00:03:50.609 --> 00:03:54.340
And so if there are disruptions in these senses, nutrition

67
00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:56.600
doesn't look like what it used to be.

68
00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:00.960
One thing that might not be as known outside of the

69
00:04:00.980 --> 00:04:04.580
community is that actually, if you lose your sense of smell, your relationship with

70
00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:08.120
people are actually changing. So one classic

71
00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:10.560
example is the newborn baby with their mom.

72
00:04:10.609 --> 00:04:12.400
They're not using vision that early.

73
00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:15.620
They're actually using smell to find the breast and then

74
00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:19.560
lactate. But also, smell is used in the context of

75
00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:21.560
mating, of relationship, of friendship.

76
00:04:21.661 --> 00:04:25.500
So losing that sense changes the way we interact with people.

77
00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:30.100
Another way of doing that is really taking away the enjoyment of

78
00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.800
life. So not liking candles, not liking going out to

79
00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:36.420
meals, changing the way you cook,

80
00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:41.100
and also being less safe than before.

81
00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:45.120
You're not able to detect whether milk could

82
00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:49.160
be spoiled, and so you might drink it and get sick, or you might even not

83
00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.700
be able to perceive a gas leak that can only be smelled.

84
00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:57.060
And these are rare occurrences, but you can understand how

85
00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.280
that knowledge that you might not be able to detect makes you feel unsafe.

86
00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:06.280
And outside of the general aspects of life

87
00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.900
that chemosensory dysfunction

88
00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:13.920
has across diagnosis, there are specific aspects

89
00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.800
that affect cancer. And so if you're not able to eat

90
00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:21.850
like you used to, there is an unintentional weight loss and malnutrition risk that,

91
00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:25.900
as you know, can contribute to general frailty or poor clinical

92
00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:29.720
outcomes. But also to decreased tolerance of cancer

93
00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:33.680
therapies. And so not being able to eat really contributes

94
00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:36.500
to the options that you have in front of you.

95
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:40.920
Generally speaking, and you will see it in one of the future slides, there is

96
00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:44.900
actually a substantial reduction in quality of life, broadly

97
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.840
speaking, that really touches people that have dysfunctions

98
00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:51.740
in smell and taste, and on top of cancer.

99
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:56.540
And other than that, basically, when patients are bringing

100
00:05:56.580 --> 00:06:00.440
up the idea that they have smell and taste dysfunction, they don't really find

101
00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:04.200
good listening ears in their family or their friends,

102
00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:08.300
nor in their clinical providers. And so this creates that feeling of

103
00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:12.160
isolation, that it's really not fostering the support

104
00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:13.500
system that we all want to

105
00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:16.960
provide.Chemosensory dysfunction,

106
00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:21.000
it's a general sentinel for a disease that it's

107
00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:24.560
under-recognized more broadly. So this is not a cancer-specific

108
00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:28.060
aspect. But when we start looking at data from even

109
00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.650
representative sample, it tends to predict a cognitive decline and

110
00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:35.360
conversion of cognitive decline into dementia in a vast

111
00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:38.780
majority of people with Parkinson's disease and Alzheimer's disease.

112
00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:42.400
We're talking about 85%, 90% of people, so it's not a

113
00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:46.400
rare occurrence. It predicts a heart failure, so

114
00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:50.280
those who have smell dysfunction, they have 30% to 40% higher

115
00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:54.220
risk of incident heart failure. It's linked to malnutrition,

116
00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:58.160
to frailty related to surgery or not, and generally speaking,

117
00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:02.220
accelerated aging, as well as there's a high

118
00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:06.120
correlation between people that lose their sense of smell and are

119
00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.700
depressed, and vice versa. Those who are depressed tend to have

120
00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:13.800
lower olfactory abilities, and those who lose their sense of smell are more

121
00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:17.640
depressed. But also, this is specifically linked to suicidal

122
00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:21.340
ideation. So it seems that losing your sense of smell

123
00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:24.370
actually has a breadth of bad outcomes.

124
00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:28.740
When it comes to cancer, we know that approximately 60% of

125
00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.200
patients with cancer have or report having some

126
00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:36.880
form of smell dysfunction, but 93% of people

127
00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:40.560
experience taste dysfunction in the course of their disorder.

128
00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:44.520
So again, this is not like a minor group of

129
00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:48.160
patients. It's not a rare set of symptoms, and it's

130
00:07:48.380 --> 00:07:49.560
generally unaddressed.

131
00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:54.040
When we start looking at research more broadly, there are almost four and a half

132
00:07:54.180 --> 00:07:57.740
million studies in PubMed just by looking at cancer in

133
00:07:57.820 --> 00:08:01.700
humans, and only 0.1% includes a mention of

134
00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:04.350
smell and taste. So although

135
00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:08.870
it's growing, we can see that in the latest year, there's more and more

136
00:08:08.900 --> 00:08:12.550
attention to this, it's still a very marginal area of

137
00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:16.080
research and clinical practice that we hope can change.

138
00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:21.850
Chemosensory dysfunction is often thought of as a symptom of

139
00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:25.640
particularly of head and neck cancer, of course, like in the

140
00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:29.500
nose, in the mouth. There are structures that allow us to

141
00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:34.420
translate the chemical information into electrical signal for the brain.

142
00:08:34.821 --> 00:08:38.680
And so the tumors might be there. Surgery might take out those tumors

143
00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:42.081
and allow for sensory dysfunction to emerge.

144
00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:46.160
But this is actually not the only case, that there's a variety of other

145
00:08:46.240 --> 00:08:49.880
types of cancers at different stages across the

146
00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:53.540
lifespan that actually present with smell and taste dysfunction,

147
00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:56.320
alone or in association with therapy.

148
00:08:56.460 --> 00:09:00.120
Chemotherapy, radiation, or surgery can all

149
00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:04.160
impact in a transient way or even more permanent, like at

150
00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:07.480
the end of the treatment, the appearance of chemosensory

151
00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:09.380
dysfunction and permanence.

152
00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:15.420
This is a problem because when we start looking at representative data on how

153
00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:18.880
chemosensory dysfunction in cancer is linked to life

154
00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:22.860
satisfaction, we start seeing that this becomes a

155
00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:23.320
huge

156
00:09:24.540 --> 00:09:26.880
symptom that reduces quality of life.

157
00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.800
So these two graphs are taken from an

158
00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:32.480
analysis run on the National

159
00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:37.189
Health and Nutritional Examination Survey or NHANES,

160
00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:39.620
that looks at more than 3,000 people,

161
00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:44.660
again, representative samples in the US, where we find

162
00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:48.680
14% reports taste dysfunction, 22% reports

163
00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:52.160
smell dysfunction, and 10% reports both.

164
00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:56.120
And there is a 40% reduction of

165
00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:00.420
odds ratio of experiencing a satisfying life if you're

166
00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:03.740
experiencing smell dysfunction and 60% if you're

167
00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:05.460
experiencing taste dysfunction.

168
00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:09.040
So that's a big chunk of the experience.

169
00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:13.720
When we start digging a little bit into what taste dysfunction or smell

170
00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:17.640
dysfunction can highlight, we can see that at least 50%

171
00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:21.060
of people, based on data from Alyssa Nolden at the University of

172
00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:22.580
Massachusetts Amherst,

173
00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:28.440
patients that are undergoing the second or third

174
00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:32.440
cycle or chemotherapy, one in two really reports that there

175
00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:35.240
are changes in the way the food tastes.

176
00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:39.220
And if you look at the bars in the graph, the gray bars indicate people

177
00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:43.140
experiencing taste changes versus those who don't, in

178
00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:46.840
black. You can see that there is a variety of GI symptoms,

179
00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:50.660
constipation, feeling bloated, difficulty swallowing, weight gain, weight

180
00:10:50.740 --> 00:10:54.620
loss, that is magnified in association with

181
00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:55.720
taste changes,

182
00:10:56.720 --> 00:10:59.880
irrespective of the cancer and the stage that they're at.

183
00:11:01.180 --> 00:11:05.080
And we're trying to figure out why might we not really

184
00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:09.020
look at what happens in chemosensory dysfunction.

185
00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:12.780
It's not something that is traditionally part of the

186
00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:16.700
clinical path, and one of the reasons might be that we don't have the words

187
00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:19.080
to actually talk about smell and taste.

188
00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:22.920
And so our patients, if they're not prompted, they're not really able

189
00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:23.800
to

190
00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:27.240
report accurately where the problem might be.

191
00:11:27.350 --> 00:11:31.120
And this is a study that I conducted with a former postdoc of mine, and it's

192
00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:33.540
not in the cancer space, but in general.

193
00:11:33.560 --> 00:11:37.260
And we ask people, "Can you think about your awareness and your value of

194
00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:41.200
different senses?" We ran this study on more than 1,000

195
00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:44.900
people across 20 countries, and 62% of

196
00:11:44.980 --> 00:11:48.960
people say, "If forced, I could totally give up the sense of smell." So

197
00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.980
people don't generally have awareness and wording to detect what smell

198
00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:57.020
is doing in their life and what might be the source of some

199
00:11:57.120 --> 00:11:58.240
benefits from it.

200
00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:03.780
But now it's the time to eat candy, and so you all have your

201
00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:05.910
packets, or most of you have your packets.

202
00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.760
If you don't, there's some in the front that you're welcome to take.

203
00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:13.620
And so we're trying to dissociate here the experience of smell and

204
00:12:13.740 --> 00:12:17.540
taste and flavor, and trying to see how we can help

205
00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:21.180
patients that are experiencing smell and taste changes to

206
00:12:21.300 --> 00:12:24.980
actually more accurately report and probe

207
00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:26.980
more accurately where the problem might be.

208
00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:31.200
So what I'm going to ask you to do is to take out that blue thing, like the nose

209
00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.236
clipper, and put it on your nose.And it doesn't

210
00:12:35.336 --> 00:12:39.216
hurt. It squishes a little bit. And then take one of

211
00:12:39.296 --> 00:12:40.996
the jelly beans that you find

212
00:12:42.436 --> 00:12:46.236
and place it in your mouth. And I would like for you to chew

213
00:12:46.996 --> 00:12:48.096
that jelly bean with

214
00:12:48.976 --> 00:12:49.176
your

215
00:12:50.256 --> 00:12:51.536
clip on the nose.

216
00:12:53.956 --> 00:12:55.856
And I would like to know what is your experience.

217
00:12:56.076 --> 00:12:59.616
If you have to describe what is happening right now in your

218
00:12:59.676 --> 00:13:02.056
mouth, how would you describe what you're eating?

219
00:13:10.176 --> 00:13:13.816
It is muted. It is muted, I hear. But what is it?

220
00:13:14.076 --> 00:13:18.016
We know these are jelly beans, so we have some priors of what

221
00:13:18.056 --> 00:13:19.596
we might be tasting like.

222
00:13:22.056 --> 00:13:24.156
Sweet. Somebody says sweet.

223
00:13:25.745 --> 00:13:26.476
That's good.

224
00:13:29.176 --> 00:13:30.836
Well, but you don't have your clip.

225
00:13:31.916 --> 00:13:33.636
Oh my, I took it out. Well, that's the whole point.

226
00:13:36.516 --> 00:13:40.476
So basically, what happens right now is that most of you are going to experience

227
00:13:40.516 --> 00:13:44.336
something that is related to sweet, maybe sour, depending on the jelly bean that

228
00:13:44.376 --> 00:13:47.756
you have. But it's really hard to pinpoint what is the

229
00:13:47.776 --> 00:13:51.506
flavor that you have. So what you're experiencing right now is

230
00:13:51.536 --> 00:13:55.466
taste. Sweet, sour. If we had other stimuli, it

231
00:13:55.476 --> 00:13:59.376
could be umami, it could be salty. That information is

232
00:13:59.416 --> 00:14:03.056
what taste is like. When you remove the clip, that's when you

233
00:14:03.236 --> 00:14:07.196
start having the experience of what olfaction brings into

234
00:14:07.206 --> 00:14:11.176
the flavor matrix. And so only when you remove the clip, you can say

235
00:14:11.236 --> 00:14:15.136
that that might be lemon. And so you can identify which kind of sweet,

236
00:14:15.316 --> 00:14:19.296
sour experience you are having. And this tells you that olfaction

237
00:14:19.316 --> 00:14:23.126
plays a much stronger role than people think in describing

238
00:14:23.456 --> 00:14:25.716
taste and food experiences. Right?

239
00:14:25.796 --> 00:14:29.236
So I would say that it has been generally quantified that

240
00:14:29.356 --> 00:14:33.096
80% of the food experience, of the flavor experience, come actually

241
00:14:33.136 --> 00:14:35.776
from the nose rather than from the mouth.

242
00:14:36.396 --> 00:14:39.596
But your patients are going to come to you and tell you, "I have a problem with my

243
00:14:39.636 --> 00:14:43.596
food. It's my taste. I can't taste a thing." And you have to be able

244
00:14:43.676 --> 00:14:47.656
to differentiate whether the problem is really in the mouth, it is in the nose, or

245
00:14:47.696 --> 00:14:49.436
it is on the integration of the two.

246
00:14:52.416 --> 00:14:56.156
So taste, as we said, it's not just taste, although that's the word that people

247
00:14:56.256 --> 00:14:58.836
use. It could be orthonasal olfaction.

248
00:14:58.916 --> 00:15:02.776
So if you were to take that jelly bean and break it in two and

249
00:15:02.976 --> 00:15:06.716
smell it with your nose, that information is what is processed by the

250
00:15:06.756 --> 00:15:10.596
orthonasal olfactory system. When you removed the clip,

251
00:15:10.696 --> 00:15:13.455
that is retronasal olfactory information.

252
00:15:13.596 --> 00:15:17.376
So you were chewing your food, and the molecules went up from

253
00:15:17.776 --> 00:15:21.216
your throat up to the nose, behind the bridge of the glasses,

254
00:15:21.716 --> 00:15:25.606
and the olfactory receptors were able to bind to some of

255
00:15:25.676 --> 00:15:29.256
those chemicals. Taste, instead, is what we said, like this

256
00:15:29.476 --> 00:15:33.176
broad painting of sweet and sour and salty and umami.

257
00:15:33.796 --> 00:15:36.876
And then we have a third system, which is called the

258
00:15:36.896 --> 00:15:39.976
chemesthesis, which mediates a series of

259
00:15:40.016 --> 00:15:43.536
experiences related to cooling and warming or even

260
00:15:43.596 --> 00:15:47.276
carbonation. So if you give one of your patients, like you

261
00:15:47.336 --> 00:15:51.216
take out an alcohol wipe and you give it to your patient and say, "Smell

262
00:15:51.296 --> 00:15:55.116
this. Can you smell?" Most people, even those that completely

263
00:15:55.126 --> 00:15:59.026
lost their sense of smell, can actually say, "Yes, I smell something." But

264
00:15:59.036 --> 00:16:03.016
that's because this alcohol activates the trigeminal system.

265
00:16:03.056 --> 00:16:06.876
And so what we're really measuring there is chemesthesis rather than olfaction.

266
00:16:08.816 --> 00:16:12.726
When we try to put names to the different phenotypes of what

267
00:16:12.856 --> 00:16:16.796
smell and taste dysfunction look like, we can have the complete loss of the sense

268
00:16:16.816 --> 00:16:20.296
of smell, so people cannot smell any odor no matter what.

269
00:16:20.696 --> 00:16:24.416
They can be born with this condition, which is called anosmia, or they can

270
00:16:24.456 --> 00:16:28.416
acquire it over time. In cancer, that would be generally acquired.

271
00:16:28.896 --> 00:16:32.516
Hyposmia, instead, it's the reduction of the experience of

272
00:16:32.936 --> 00:16:35.436
orthonasal smells or retronasal smells.

273
00:16:36.196 --> 00:16:39.616
Hyperosmia, which often is linked to

274
00:16:39.916 --> 00:16:43.776
chemotherapy, is the experience of hypersensitization to the

275
00:16:43.796 --> 00:16:47.636
presence of odors. And so everything feels magnified,

276
00:16:48.336 --> 00:16:51.496
every odor feels magnified. And then we have parosmia.

277
00:16:51.555 --> 00:16:55.496
So you might remember when I talked about brushing

278
00:16:55.555 --> 00:16:59.356
your teeth and going to a dumpster trip, that is

279
00:16:59.396 --> 00:17:03.236
what parosmia might feel like. There's a distortion in the experience of what the

280
00:17:03.396 --> 00:17:06.936
odor source should generally smell like, and people are

281
00:17:06.997 --> 00:17:10.846
quite disoriented and negatively affected by

282
00:17:10.876 --> 00:17:14.356
it. And by the end, we have phantosmia, which are olfactory

283
00:17:14.396 --> 00:17:18.036
hallucinations. And so the idea that there is no odor

284
00:17:18.056 --> 00:17:21.856
source that can give us molecule that the person experiences, but

285
00:17:21.916 --> 00:17:25.876
nevertheless, the brain encodes information that comes out in the

286
00:17:25.936 --> 00:17:27.696
form of a smell perceived.

287
00:17:29.116 --> 00:17:32.836
Similarly, when we go to taste, we can have ageusia or a

288
00:17:32.876 --> 00:17:35.556
complete loss of taste. This is very rare.

289
00:17:36.136 --> 00:17:39.616
So usually the assumption is if people come to you with a taste

290
00:17:39.796 --> 00:17:40.156
issue,

291
00:17:41.576 --> 00:17:45.416
8 out of 10 times it's going to be a smell issue, but we need to

292
00:17:45.456 --> 00:17:49.396
discriminate the two. Hypogeusia is the reduced experience of

293
00:17:49.476 --> 00:17:51.636
salt, savory, sour, et cetera.

294
00:17:52.476 --> 00:17:56.316
And then one of the most common issues actually comes with dysgeusia.

295
00:17:56.416 --> 00:17:58.315
So distortions in smell and taste.

296
00:17:58.356 --> 00:18:00.716
It comes as metal mouth or metallic taste

297
00:18:01.776 --> 00:18:05.756
in the mouth, or even extreme bitter exposure.

298
00:18:06.776 --> 00:18:10.136
Extreme bitter experiences to stimuli that might not be bitter

299
00:18:10.196 --> 00:18:13.936
themselves. And then we have xerostomia, so a lack of

300
00:18:13.956 --> 00:18:17.856
saliva, like dryness in the tongue that actually changes the way

301
00:18:17.936 --> 00:18:20.556
we perceive flavor, even if the

302
00:18:22.096 --> 00:18:23.336
receptors might be

303
00:18:23.396 --> 00:18:27.272
intact.When we try to think

304
00:18:27.332 --> 00:18:28.692
about what providers

305
00:18:29.692 --> 00:18:32.352
know about chemosensory function,

306
00:18:33.552 --> 00:18:36.892
what we see is that at least 15% of clinicians

307
00:18:37.472 --> 00:18:40.312
are able to distinguish taste from flavors.

308
00:18:40.392 --> 00:18:44.372
So they might have been exposed to one of the jelly bean tests as we

309
00:18:44.412 --> 00:18:48.112
have described before, but otherwise, most people talk about

310
00:18:48.392 --> 00:18:52.252
taste in general. And 44% of oncology clinicians

311
00:18:52.332 --> 00:18:56.072
actually report that their patients with taste alterations tend to

312
00:18:56.112 --> 00:18:59.092
experience this symptom as very important.

313
00:18:59.732 --> 00:19:01.732
And so what do we do once we

314
00:19:01.792 --> 00:19:04.872
can detect

315
00:19:05.692 --> 00:19:07.732
smell and taste dysfunction? What can we do?

316
00:19:07.842 --> 00:19:11.492
And so there's a problem with measuring it, and there's also a problem with how to

317
00:19:11.532 --> 00:19:14.072
address it. Currently, we don't have pharmacological

318
00:19:15.092 --> 00:19:18.972
solutions to reverse the smell dysfunction or taste dysfunction that

319
00:19:18.992 --> 00:19:19.632
really works.

320
00:19:21.092 --> 00:19:23.932
So what we try to do is to actually create

321
00:19:24.532 --> 00:19:28.432
quick ways to change and to train clinicians.

322
00:19:28.512 --> 00:19:32.472
So we ran this quick study with 38 clinicians at Fox Chase in

323
00:19:32.512 --> 00:19:36.492
Philadelphia. We had 24% of them report that they

324
00:19:36.532 --> 00:19:40.292
had some formal training in taste and smell, but 42%

325
00:19:40.512 --> 00:19:44.312
lacked the confidence to have conversations about taste and smell changes

326
00:19:44.392 --> 00:19:47.812
with their patients. What we did was to create a

327
00:19:47.852 --> 00:19:51.712
podcast, like 30 minutes, try to do a little bit of education

328
00:19:51.892 --> 00:19:55.492
on what is the epidemiology of chemosensory dysfunction in

329
00:19:55.592 --> 00:19:59.342
cancer as well, what are the difference, much like what we've

330
00:19:59.372 --> 00:20:02.912
reviewed in this talk. And just this 30-minute

331
00:20:03.032 --> 00:20:06.672
session actually made them way more confident in their experience to have

332
00:20:06.732 --> 00:20:08.372
conversation with their patients.

333
00:20:09.512 --> 00:20:13.472
So if we were to decide how to measure smell and taste and flavor,

334
00:20:13.652 --> 00:20:17.372
like in this paper, which is a consensus paper, we have more than

335
00:20:17.412 --> 00:20:21.342
100 measures to do so. And so one of the things that we can

336
00:20:21.372 --> 00:20:25.172
easily do and that we're trying in connection with Fox Chase is to

337
00:20:25.232 --> 00:20:28.812
include in EPIC a quick question about dysgeusia or

338
00:20:28.932 --> 00:20:32.632
smell dysfunction, and trying to see, across

339
00:20:32.732 --> 00:20:36.152
cancer and diagnosis and over time, what is the

340
00:20:36.232 --> 00:20:39.592
self-report. This is very effective when it comes to taste.

341
00:20:40.052 --> 00:20:43.952
There are also some quick tests that take up to two minutes or five minutes

342
00:20:43.992 --> 00:20:46.992
at most, and you can go more in-depth with the

343
00:20:47.032 --> 00:20:50.972
evaluation. When it comes to taste, the solution is the best way to

344
00:20:51.172 --> 00:20:54.962
assess taste function, but it's highly impractical,

345
00:20:55.092 --> 00:20:57.582
so there are some taste strips that can be used.

346
00:20:58.872 --> 00:21:02.772
Very quickly, there are some things that work that would symptom management like

347
00:21:02.812 --> 00:21:05.132
flavor enhancement, put more salt, garlic.

348
00:21:05.172 --> 00:21:08.872
Of course, the salt can have some risk with cardiovascular issues, so

349
00:21:09.332 --> 00:21:13.312
we need to be mindful of that. Individualized dietary counseling has

350
00:21:13.352 --> 00:21:16.012
been particularly effective whenever possible.

351
00:21:16.572 --> 00:21:20.452
Clinician education helps, as well as eating cold or frozen food

352
00:21:20.632 --> 00:21:23.592
using plastic utensils to reduce metal mouth.

353
00:21:24.132 --> 00:21:25.632
For this, there is some

354
00:21:27.592 --> 00:21:29.232
evidence that has been

355
00:21:30.692 --> 00:21:34.512
validated. What did not work but is actually still suggested

356
00:21:34.552 --> 00:21:35.781
in some of the patient

357
00:21:36.592 --> 00:21:40.492
information that goes around is the use of zinc sulfate or general

358
00:21:40.572 --> 00:21:44.192
