00:29:29.552 --> 00:29:31.572
qualities are new.

494
00:29:32.372 --> 00:29:36.152
And so we're fascinated by how the sense of taste is constantly

495
00:29:36.232 --> 00:29:38.672
renewing, yet perceptually so constant.

496
00:29:40.772 --> 00:29:44.632
So I was told this was a CME class, and

497
00:29:44.752 --> 00:29:47.372
so I had learning objectives. And

498
00:29:48.312 --> 00:29:51.832
what I'd like you to appreciate by the end of this session

499
00:29:52.052 --> 00:29:56.032
is to have an understanding of the normal mechanisms that

500
00:29:56.092 --> 00:29:58.052
underlie taste bud cell renewal.

501
00:29:59.472 --> 00:30:02.772
Understand that there are pathways that regulate taste

502
00:30:02.812 --> 00:30:06.712
homeostasis that are also implicated in cancer, and then

503
00:30:06.792 --> 00:30:09.912
how cancer pathways that are targeted

504
00:30:10.672 --> 00:30:14.392
specifically affect different aspects of taste bud cell

505
00:30:14.432 --> 00:30:18.112
turnover. And then finally, I'll introduce you to some

506
00:30:18.192 --> 00:30:21.592
data or some new findings on our

507
00:30:22.732 --> 00:30:26.352
approaches to develop standardized taste organoids

508
00:30:26.772 --> 00:30:27.972
in both mouse and human.

509
00:30:29.692 --> 00:30:29.932
So

510
00:30:31.912 --> 00:30:35.692
as you're aware, taste buds are embedded in papillae on the tongue,

511
00:30:36.112 --> 00:30:37.872
and these are... There we

512
00:30:37.932 --> 00:30:41.504
go.So in the front of the tongue

513
00:30:41.844 --> 00:30:45.324
