00:58:44.940 --> 00:58:48.820
And so far, I think you have to be 18 to be an organ donor, and so

1000
00:58:48.860 --> 00:58:50.660
our youngest donor has been 21.

1001
00:58:53.240 --> 00:58:55.260
Hi, thanks for the talk. I have a question.

1002
00:58:55.340 --> 00:58:59.260
It's that since the taste bud cells come back every two

1003
00:58:59.280 --> 00:58:59.790
months,

1004
00:59:00.640 --> 00:59:04.080
so I was wondering, will the smell or the taste come back

1005
00:59:04.620 --> 00:59:08.560
just naturally after some time of the chemotherapy?

1006
00:59:09.700 --> 00:59:09.920
So,

1007
00:59:10.940 --> 00:59:12.420
I don't know anything about smell.

1008
00:59:13.480 --> 00:59:15.400
So I don't know anything about smell. Yeah.

1009
00:59:16.140 --> 00:59:18.020
But with taste, so it's interesting.

1010
00:59:18.180 --> 00:59:19.040
So I think

1011
00:59:21.840 --> 00:59:25.480
mice that get hedgehog, a smoothened

1012
00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:26.240
antagonist,

1013
00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:27.980
right? So

1014
00:59:28.840 --> 00:59:31.040
Archana did this study, actually.

1015
00:59:31.480 --> 00:59:34.980
So they put mice on the drug long enough to know the taste buds were gone,

1016
00:59:35.360 --> 00:59:38.600
took the mice off the drug, and watched the taste buds come back.

1017
00:59:38.990 --> 00:59:42.780
And the ones that came back, came back fully, but not all of them did.

1018
00:59:43.440 --> 00:59:45.240
And they were looking in the fungiform field,

1019
00:59:46.060 --> 00:59:47.560
not in the circumvallate field.

1020
00:59:48.420 --> 00:59:52.200
And I've

1021
00:59:52.540 --> 00:59:56.440
anecdotally talked to one colleague who's a radiation oncologist

1022
00:59:56.580 --> 01:00:00.480
that treats head and neck cancers, and she had a patient

1023
01:00:00.540 --> 01:00:04.480
that she treated repeatedly with both

1024
01:00:05.080 --> 01:00:07.640
head and neck radiation, but also with

1025
01:00:08.860 --> 01:00:11.640
smoothened antagonists. And that person

1026
01:00:12.280 --> 01:00:16.180
gradually just lost their sense of taste. It just never came back.

1027
01:00:16.260 --> 01:00:16.700
So I think,

1028
01:00:18.660 --> 01:00:21.900
yes, it can come back, but I think that

1029
01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:25.800
it also doesn't come back the way it was before.

1030
01:00:26.780 --> 01:00:30.480
And it may be how the brain adapts to the new taste array,

1031
01:00:30.700 --> 01:00:34.420
and if there's enough plasticity for you to limp along with that level

1032
01:00:34.840 --> 01:00:37.240
of a taste periphery, then taste seems normal.

1033
01:00:38.060 --> 01:00:38.940
Alternatively,

1034
01:00:40.640 --> 01:00:44.060
there are head and neck cancer patients that have a permanently

1035
01:00:44.180 --> 01:00:47.920
disrupted sense of taste, and anecdotally they say,

1036
01:00:49.110 --> 01:00:52.950
"Yes, I can taste everything, but it doesn't taste like it used

1037
01:00:53.020 --> 01:00:57.000
to." So they're very aware of that, and what's interesting about

1038
01:00:57.960 --> 01:01:00.760
that is that that's not detectable

1039
01:01:01.680 --> 01:01:05.520
with these conventional taste and smell tests

1040
01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:08.440
that patients are given because they taste just fine.

1041
01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:11.820
It's the composite that is distorted for them.

1042
01:01:13.920 --> 01:01:15.440
That's very interesting. Thank you.

1043
01:01:15.760 --> 01:01:19.590
Thanks.We are

1044
01:01:19.750 --> 01:01:20.170
at time.

1045
01:01:22.050 --> 01:01:24.650
Well, thank you, Linda. Thanks for the question.

1046
01:01:39.250 --> 01:01:43.130
Okay. Thanks, everybody. This is clearly a very engaged group because you could

1047
01:01:43.190 --> 01:01:46.010
be out at happy hour, but you've decided to stay here with us.

1048
01:01:46.090 --> 01:01:48.010
So we're really, really grateful for that.

1049
01:01:49.630 --> 01:01:51.319
Now, I wanted to start by thanking Dr.

1050
01:01:51.530 --> 01:01:54.130
Palmer as well for getting us here together.

1051
01:01:54.790 --> 01:01:56.730
I've traveled all the way from Melbourne in Australia.

1052
01:01:56.770 --> 01:01:59.110
I don't know if there's any other Australians in the audience.

1053
01:02:00.210 --> 01:02:04.050
No, I'm glad for you because I nearly had as much time in the air as I will have on

1054
01:02:04.090 --> 01:02:04.590
the ground.

1055
01:02:05.630 --> 01:02:09.390
And so that flight is no joke. But as I said, it's really, really

1056
01:02:09.450 --> 01:02:13.150
great to be here. And to hear someone in the room say that this

1057
01:02:13.190 --> 01:02:16.070
wasn't part of their world until they've just come here, and now they understand

1058
01:02:16.110 --> 01:02:18.290
about this is our kind of dream come true.

1059
01:02:18.410 --> 01:02:18.550
So,

1060
01:02:19.470 --> 01:02:23.290
I've been working to bridge chemosensory and clinical oncology

1061
01:02:23.370 --> 01:02:27.110
worlds for 15 years. I trained originally as a dietician,

1062
01:02:27.350 --> 01:02:30.990
and my PhD was born out of a frustration I had

1063
01:02:31.230 --> 01:02:31.570
to

1064
01:02:32.750 --> 01:02:35.050
not be able to help my patients as much as I wanted to.

1065
01:02:35.100 --> 01:02:38.290
And so I would hear people, especially in the head and neck cancer setting,

1066
01:02:39.110 --> 01:02:42.690
complain about taste dysfunction and problems that were getting in the way of them

1067
01:02:42.750 --> 01:02:45.430
having an adequate diet and enjoying their food.

1068
01:02:45.610 --> 01:02:49.550
And so it led me to undertake a PhD exploring the influence

1069
01:02:49.590 --> 01:02:53.330
of chemotherapy on taste dysfunction, nutritional intake, and food

1070
01:02:53.370 --> 01:02:53.950
enjoyment.

1071
01:02:54.910 --> 01:02:58.830
And what you'll hear today is some of the learnings from that journey over

1072
01:02:58.870 --> 01:03:02.810
the last 15 years. But we didn't ask who was in the room, and

1073
01:03:02.870 --> 01:03:06.260
so I think we've got a mix of clinician researchers, but

1074
01:03:06.690 --> 01:03:10.640
maybe we just see a show of hands if you describe yourself just

1075
01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:13.190
as a pure researcher, no one lets you near a patient.

1076
01:03:14.350 --> 01:03:14.650
Okay.

1077
01:03:15.710 --> 01:03:18.629
A few researchers. And what about clinicians?

1078
01:03:18.690 --> 01:03:21.770
You treat patients, you see patients. Okay, good.

1079
01:03:22.110 --> 01:03:23.150
And what if you do both?

1080
01:03:24.350 --> 01:03:27.149
Everyone. Well, most people, thank you, delve into both worlds.

1081
01:03:27.190 --> 01:03:29.750
So we've got a good mix of people, which is wonderful.

1082
01:03:30.670 --> 01:03:30.910
Okay.

1083
01:03:31.930 --> 01:03:33.830
At the moment, I work in three key areas.

1084
01:03:33.870 --> 01:03:37.740
It's gynecological cancer policy, women's

1085
01:03:37.770 --> 01:03:40.690
health research, and my passion area, which is gastronomy.

1086
01:03:40.710 --> 01:03:44.370
And I think I might be one of the only people in the world who have a

1087
01:03:44.410 --> 01:03:46.650
Masters of Dietetics and a Masters of Gastronomy.

1088
01:03:46.750 --> 01:03:49.950
So, the food science and the love of food come together nicely.

1089
01:03:50.750 --> 01:03:54.230
Okay. So what are the problems in cancer care?

1090
01:03:54.730 --> 01:03:56.270
Well, we know that

1091
01:03:57.770 --> 01:04:01.370
sensory and hedonic changes are common, but no one's talking about them.

1092
01:04:01.430 --> 01:04:04.370
And when we do talk about them, we don't really know how to treat them.

1093
01:04:05.150 --> 01:04:08.670
And so it is such that these issues aren't

1094
01:04:08.710 --> 01:04:12.460
really prioritized in the pre-treatment setting, in the pre-habilitation

1095
01:04:12.690 --> 01:04:16.260
setting. When we tell people what to expect from cancer treatment, we talk to them

1096
01:04:16.350 --> 01:04:18.750
about nausea, about hair loss, about weight loss.

1097
01:04:19.210 --> 01:04:22.830
But taste dysfunction and smell issues do not

1098
01:04:23.730 --> 01:04:25.830
routinely come up in that context.

1099
01:04:25.890 --> 01:04:28.850
And so when these things do come up, people are taken

1100
01:04:28.890 --> 01:04:32.790
unaware. They're also not necessarily found in isolation.

1101
01:04:32.890 --> 01:04:36.570
So, taste and smell problems go together with nausea, with

1102
01:04:36.650 --> 01:04:40.350
changes in appetite. And in speaking with colleagues at Fox

1103
01:04:40.410 --> 01:04:43.570
Chase Center, what they described is that their

1104
01:04:44.310 --> 01:04:48.260
nutrition counseling referrals come from a point of weight loss and

1105
01:04:48.310 --> 01:04:51.850
malnutrition. So their counseling referrals, sorry, for taste

1106
01:04:51.870 --> 01:04:53.430
dysfunction and how they note that.

1107
01:04:53.490 --> 01:04:57.480
So what that means is it's often not until a patient is experiencing

1108
01:04:57.510 --> 01:05:01.350
malnutrition risk or malnutrition that they then get counseled and what

1109
01:05:01.430 --> 01:05:04.710
comes out of that session is that, "Oh, we've got problems with the way that food

1110
01:05:04.830 --> 01:05:05.430
tastes." So,

1111
01:05:06.370 --> 01:05:09.010
we're not being proactive about it, and

1112
01:05:10.210 --> 01:05:14.090
it is confusing for patients. And there's a really neat term, it's a

1113
01:05:14.130 --> 01:05:18.070
terrible term, it's quite depressing, but a term that Santini gave

1114
01:05:18.150 --> 01:05:21.630
to the cluster or symptoms that happen in isolation called orphan

1115
01:05:21.730 --> 01:05:25.550
symptoms. And these are symptoms that aren't routinely or

1116
01:05:25.590 --> 01:05:26.630
spontaneously

1117
01:05:28.590 --> 01:05:32.170
mentioned by patients, and they're not routinely assessed by clinicians, and so

1118
01:05:32.230 --> 01:05:35.370
they remain unaddressed in a clinical oncology setting.

1119
01:05:35.630 --> 01:05:38.770
There's an ESMO guideline for the clinicians in the room

1120
01:05:39.529 --> 01:05:42.210
on this. And some of the other symptoms in that

1121
01:05:43.190 --> 01:05:46.950
subset include ubiquitous symptoms that aren't life-threatening

1122
01:05:46.970 --> 01:05:50.350
but are really bothersome. So things like coughing, like hiccupping,

1123
01:05:50.750 --> 01:05:54.390
restless leg syndrome. And you can see by

1124
01:05:54.430 --> 01:05:58.300
mentioning those that it's no surprise they don't feature in a hierarchy of

1125
01:05:58.330 --> 01:06:02.110
symptoms. But they are symptoms that do cause

1126
01:06:02.170 --> 01:06:05.930
great bother to people. We know that food is not only a source of

1127
01:06:05.990 --> 01:06:09.940
nutrition, but it's a way of understanding the world and it's

1128
01:06:10.030 --> 01:06:13.710
about cultural identity. And so during cancer treatment, those shifts

1129
01:06:14.290 --> 01:06:17.670
in food's role from a source of enjoyment to perhaps a source of

1130
01:06:18.070 --> 01:06:20.950
medicine or treatment is quite a significant shift.

1131
01:06:22.210 --> 01:06:23.970
These problems are underreported.

1132
01:06:24.010 --> 01:06:27.870
Like I said, when they do come up, there's confusion about what the referral

1133
01:06:27.990 --> 01:06:31.390
pathway should be. So Alyssa Nolden and colleagues published a paper

1134
01:06:31.400 --> 01:06:34.970
recently, where clinicians were interviewed.

1135
01:06:35.810 --> 01:06:39.110
What do you do when chemosensory issues arise?

1136
01:06:39.630 --> 01:06:43.350
Who do you refer to? And there was a diversity in those referral pathways.

1137
01:06:43.390 --> 01:06:46.410
They include dentists, dieticians, acupuncturists,

1138
01:06:46.810 --> 01:06:48.990
otolaryngologists, I think I've said that right,

1139
01:06:50.290 --> 01:06:54.250
and taste and smell centers. So, this isn't the fault of clinicians, but

1140
01:06:54.370 --> 01:06:56.150
it's painting the picture that we don't know what to do.

1141
01:06:56.210 --> 01:06:59.190
We don't treat these symptoms very well at all.

1142
01:06:59.600 --> 01:07:03.350
And because what I'll go on to explain is because we don't accurately

1143
01:07:03.450 --> 01:07:07.430
identify the issue at hand, we can't go on to design

1144
01:07:07.470 --> 01:07:10.570
and test interventions like we would for some of the other symptoms.

1145
01:07:11.030 --> 01:07:14.700
And so there is a lack of evidence for these long-term clinical

1146
01:07:14.750 --> 01:07:18.010
interventions that are successful and things happen more by trial and

1147
01:07:18.070 --> 01:07:21.722
error.So

1148
01:07:22.202 --> 01:07:26.002
fast forward 15 years, and I went and spoke to

1149
01:07:26.302 --> 01:07:29.702
clinicians or the nutrition department really at Australia's

1150
01:07:29.742 --> 01:07:31.402
leading cancer hospital,

1151
01:07:32.302 --> 01:07:34.542
and wanted to know what current practice is.

1152
01:07:34.592 --> 01:07:37.142
Are people talking about taste and smell problems?

1153
01:07:37.222 --> 01:07:40.542
How is it being discussed with patients? What's being documented?

1154
01:07:40.622 --> 01:07:42.802
How are you managing this in practice?

1155
01:07:43.562 --> 01:07:47.522
And I sat with the manager and she showed me a tool, which I'll show you

1156
01:07:47.562 --> 01:07:50.422
in a moment. It's our standardized PGSGA.

1157
01:07:50.962 --> 01:07:54.942
It's a patient-generated subjective global assessment, a validated tool

1158
01:07:55.002 --> 01:07:55.682
for assessing

1159
01:07:56.982 --> 01:08:00.962
nutrition in oncology patients. And there's

1160
01:08:01.022 --> 01:08:04.742
a whole range of tick boxes, have you lost weight? What have your symptoms been?

1161
01:08:05.142 --> 01:08:08.662
And there's a whole range of those, and one of them includes that things taste or

1162
01:08:08.702 --> 01:08:09.232
smell funny.

1163
01:08:10.602 --> 01:08:12.642
So I'll show you that now. You can see that one circled there.

1164
01:08:13.102 --> 01:08:17.052
So, there's some weight history, and then there's the types of symptoms that people

1165
01:08:17.083 --> 01:08:20.762
are occurring that might have contributed to that change in weight or

1166
01:08:20.842 --> 01:08:22.882
nutrition risk. And so

1167
01:08:23.882 --> 01:08:27.742
this form is uploaded into the electronic medical record.

1168
01:08:28.032 --> 01:08:31.842
And we looked at a patient's and they didn't have that box ticked, and I said to

1169
01:08:31.902 --> 01:08:35.583
the manager, "Is the box not

1170
01:08:35.642 --> 01:08:39.402
ticked because they didn't have that symptom or that the dietician

1171
01:08:39.463 --> 01:08:41.422
didn't ask?" And she said, "It could be either."

1172
01:08:42.862 --> 01:08:46.463
In a rush, in a time-pressed environment, people talk about oral

1173
01:08:46.782 --> 01:08:49.842
health, they talk about weight loss, they talk about nausea.

1174
01:08:50.602 --> 01:08:53.543
Taste and smell falls further down the priority list.

1175
01:08:54.003 --> 01:08:56.482
And so we don't have good data in the electronic

1176
01:08:57.602 --> 01:08:58.602
medical record either,

1177
01:08:59.762 --> 01:09:03.083
because in time-pressured environment, often it's

1178
01:09:03.142 --> 01:09:04.222
deprioritized.

1179
01:09:06.222 --> 01:09:09.842
The patient education material that's provided is quite generic.

1180
01:09:09.942 --> 01:09:12.562
So we know that nutrition is very important in cancer.

1181
01:09:12.692 --> 01:09:16.422
And in Australia, the Cancer Council Australia is our

1182
01:09:16.463 --> 01:09:19.963
biggest charity providing evidence-based supportive care

1183
01:09:20.003 --> 01:09:23.522
information to patients. And there's a nutrition and cancer booklet.

1184
01:09:23.562 --> 01:09:24.682
It's 60 pages long.

1185
01:09:25.623 --> 01:09:27.722
It's available via PDF. It's free.

1186
01:09:27.922 --> 01:09:31.401
And within that, there's a page and a half on taste and smell problems in it.

1187
01:09:32.722 --> 01:09:36.382
I wrote that 15 years ago. That is still the resource that is being used in

1188
01:09:36.422 --> 01:09:39.882
Australia. And it's very generic, like I said,

1189
01:09:40.782 --> 01:09:44.742
but it's something, because 15 years ago, I feel like I went on a bit of

1190
01:09:44.782 --> 01:09:48.402
a PR campaign to kind of tell people all about this issue that

1191
01:09:48.782 --> 01:09:51.463
one of us in the room has discovered for the first time today.

1192
01:09:51.503 --> 01:09:55.392
And there was this awakening, and an education, and a bit of a groundswell I felt

1193
01:09:55.822 --> 01:09:59.442
in people understanding the difference between taste and flavor and chemosensory

1194
01:09:59.462 --> 01:10:02.522
and other hedonic issues. Hedonics being the study of things that are

1195
01:10:02.562 --> 01:10:04.002
pleasurable in life.

1196
01:10:04.942 --> 01:10:07.682
And people had these questions. Clinicians had the questions.

1197
01:10:07.762 --> 01:10:10.202
Patients had the questions. How long is this thing going to last for?

1198
01:10:10.242 --> 01:10:13.482
And someone asked that today. Really practical questions.

1199
01:10:13.522 --> 01:10:16.922
I'm saving a really special bottle of wine for when I finish my treatment.

1200
01:10:17.542 --> 01:10:20.002
Doctor, when should I expect to be able to drink that?

1201
01:10:20.342 --> 01:10:21.642
When should I have this special dinner?

1202
01:10:21.722 --> 01:10:23.382
These are the questions people want to know.

1203
01:10:24.242 --> 01:10:27.582
And unfortunately, clinicians were at a loss and

1204
01:10:28.582 --> 01:10:32.442
would either give false hope by saying, "Well, it should come back when chemo comes

1205
01:10:32.462 --> 01:10:33.911
back." Or, "As the chemo stops," rather.

1206
01:10:34.902 --> 01:10:38.742
Or, "I don't know, but hopefully it's transient." And so that was part of what we

1207
01:10:38.962 --> 01:10:42.322
really wanted some evidence about, and I'll go on to tell you what

1208
01:10:42.942 --> 01:10:43.682
I saw.

1209
01:10:45.502 --> 01:10:49.182
How many people in the room know about miraculin or something called miracle fruit?

1210
01:10:50.602 --> 01:10:54.082
These two do, of course. Good. So I'm not telling you something you don't know.

1211
01:10:54.182 --> 01:10:57.422
Please don't rush out and think this is a miracle cure despite its name.

1212
01:10:57.722 --> 01:10:59.942
But it is one of these things that

1213
01:11:00.742 --> 01:11:02.942
often is done in desperation by clinicians.

1214
01:11:02.982 --> 01:11:06.822
And, a decade ago, I wrote a paper entitled,

1215
01:11:07.242 --> 01:11:10.462
Taste, in inverted commas because taste is not taste as we saw,

1216
01:11:11.142 --> 01:11:13.442
is a Problem for Patients and their Clinicians.

1217
01:11:13.552 --> 01:11:17.462
And miraculin is a tropical fruit that the seed of

1218
01:11:17.502 --> 01:11:18.842
which when it's sucked

1219
01:11:20.882 --> 01:11:23.002
transfers or...

1220
01:11:24.072 --> 01:11:27.782
What's the word I'm looking for? It basically changes taste perception, so things

1221
01:11:27.822 --> 01:11:30.162
move from tasting sour to tasting sweet.

1222
01:11:30.632 --> 01:11:34.182
And so on the tropical fruit farm in Australia, when I experienced this firsthand,

1223
01:11:34.262 --> 01:11:37.682
we were all asked to do an experiment and bite into a piece of lime.

1224
01:11:37.722 --> 01:11:41.102
Of course, it's very sour. It's astringent. It's quite puckering.

1225
01:11:41.302 --> 01:11:45.102
And then you suck on this seed out of the miracle fruit, and then you bite the lime

1226
01:11:45.122 --> 01:11:47.562
again and it's sweet. It's as sweet as lemonade.

1227
01:11:48.142 --> 01:11:50.902
And this has been extracted into a tablet form.

1228
01:11:51.322 --> 01:11:55.242
The dieticians at this hospital are suggesting it at a loss for patients.

1229
01:11:55.272 --> 01:11:58.742
"Well, there's no evidence for it, but maybe try this available in the pharmacy

1230
01:11:58.822 --> 01:12:02.062
downstairs." The problem we have is that this causes a new problem.

1231
01:12:02.122 --> 01:12:04.562
This is about othering. Then suddenly everything tastes sweet.

1232
01:12:04.622 --> 01:12:07.312
Who wants their coffee to taste like sweet lemonade? I don't.

1233
01:12:07.322 --> 01:12:10.962
But people are desperate, and they're trying things.

1234
01:12:11.282 --> 01:12:14.082
Zinc supplementation in Santini's paper.

1235
01:12:14.182 --> 01:12:16.682
She reviewed the evidence of therapeutic interventions.

1236
01:12:16.802 --> 01:12:20.502
It was not found to be effective. By all means, if someone's deficient in zinc,

1237
01:12:20.562 --> 01:12:22.702
that's not good for them, that they should be supplemented.

1238
01:12:22.722 --> 01:12:26.472
But there is no wonder drug here. And so what she concluded in that

1239
01:12:26.522 --> 01:12:30.492
paper, in that clinical guideline, is that nutrition counseling and self-management

1240
01:12:30.622 --> 01:12:33.022
strategies for patient is the best that we can do right now.

1241
01:12:35.902 --> 01:12:37.602
So what do we know?

1242
01:12:39.042 --> 01:12:41.082
Let's talk about the timing issue.

1243
01:12:41.402 --> 01:12:45.162
In a group of people receiving chemotherapy for breast

1244
01:12:45.242 --> 01:12:47.362
cancer who were radiotherapy naïve,

1245
01:12:48.242 --> 01:12:52.142
we found that these symptoms were cyclical.

1246
01:12:52.222 --> 01:12:55.812
So what that means is that within an individual chemotherapy

1247
01:12:55.902 --> 01:12:57.562
cycle, the symptoms will change.

1248
01:12:59.322 --> 01:13:03.102
Originally or most commonly, patient's taste is assessed on the

1249
01:13:03.172 --> 01:13:07.102
day they come back for chemotherapy and present at the hospital, which is usually

1250
01:13:07.162 --> 01:13:11.122
two weeks or three weeks from the last chemotherapy cycle that they had.

1251
01:13:11.142 --> 01:13:14.302
And what we see is that that's normally when symptoms are at their worst,

1252
01:13:14.942 --> 01:13:16.382
sorry, at their least problematic.

1253
01:13:16.422 --> 01:13:19.922
They've had two or three weeks for things to resolve somewhat, whereas in those

1254
01:13:19.982 --> 01:13:21.622
first four to seven days, it's when

1255
01:13:23.006 --> 01:13:26.626
... the most acute problems were. And so in my study, I was able to

1256
01:13:26.686 --> 01:13:30.566
post out a taste assessment kit for patients to do at home with me, guided

1257
01:13:30.626 --> 01:13:34.566
over the phone. And it was very clear that in days four to seven of a chemotherapy

1258
01:13:34.646 --> 01:13:37.046
cycle, that taste dysfunction occurs more

1259
01:13:38.426 --> 01:13:41.746
severely than on the last day of a cycle before you start again.

1260
01:13:42.386 --> 01:13:45.626
We also saw in that group of people that two months after

1261
01:13:46.006 --> 01:13:49.726
chemotherapy had finished, that they were able to identify

1262
01:13:49.866 --> 01:13:52.966
the basic tastes again. So tastes had largely normalized.

1263
01:13:53.066 --> 01:13:53.586
However,

1264
01:13:54.986 --> 01:13:58.946
they had not received any radiotherapy, and that could

1265
01:13:59.006 --> 01:14:01.026
be for some people a year after treatment had started.

1266
01:14:01.086 --> 01:14:04.486
So they'd battled with these symptoms for an entire year.

1267
01:14:06.006 --> 01:14:09.526
People were losing weight but also gaining weight in that cohort,

1268
01:14:10.286 --> 01:14:13.446
from as much as 10 kilos in an individual person.

1269
01:14:13.846 --> 01:14:17.556
And what patients were telling me is that sometimes they bring an eating event

1270
01:14:17.646 --> 01:14:21.406
forward. So how does their diet change? It changes in a whole range of ways.

1271
01:14:22.286 --> 01:14:25.266
It may be that people are eating less and not enjoying their food as much.

1272
01:14:25.506 --> 01:14:28.726
Some people are actually bringing their food events forward to try and get rid of a

1273
01:14:28.766 --> 01:14:32.746
metallic mouth to manage their symptoms of nausea through sort

1274
01:14:32.786 --> 01:14:35.806
of dry, crunchy, salty, savory snacks, that kind of thing.

1275
01:14:37.706 --> 01:14:41.386
We know, I guess we might call it eating hygiene. We talk about sleep hygiene.

1276
01:14:41.446 --> 01:14:44.976
What is good practice? Having a good, clean, healthy mouth

1277
01:14:45.426 --> 01:14:48.916
is a good thing to be able to do. And so that

1278
01:14:48.966 --> 01:14:52.846
is something that really worked for patients, or at least

1279
01:14:53.146 --> 01:14:55.726
it was worse when there wasn't good oral hygiene there.

1280
01:14:57.906 --> 01:15:01.606
We talk about a colleague, Sara Spinelli from the University of

1281
01:15:01.666 --> 01:15:05.006
Florence in the School of Sensory Science there. I love this term.

1282
01:15:05.106 --> 01:15:07.646
She talks about sensory-nutritional opportunities.

1283
01:15:08.166 --> 01:15:11.926
So we haven't tested interventions that work, but what we

1284
01:15:12.086 --> 01:15:16.006
do know from patients' stories is that some things work for

1285
01:15:16.106 --> 01:15:19.206
some people, and we need to hang on to that and we need to test.

1286
01:15:19.246 --> 01:15:19.886
We need to

1287
01:15:20.926 --> 01:15:23.766
collect data around those things. We need to go back. We need to monitor.

1288
01:15:23.806 --> 01:15:27.746
We need to change our practice. And there's a collection of things that

1289
01:15:28.046 --> 01:15:31.096
are useful and equally Valentina talked about some of those.

1290
01:15:31.725 --> 01:15:35.326
In my study, we saw, I tested a standardized sweet food and a

1291
01:15:35.406 --> 01:15:38.976
standardized savory food at different points during the chemotherapy

1292
01:15:39.206 --> 01:15:43.026
treatment trajectory, and people went off sweet foods

1293
01:15:43.126 --> 01:15:47.106
more often, or more so than they went off savory

1294
01:15:47.146 --> 01:15:50.586
foods. And so what do we prescribe to patients who aren't eating during cancer

1295
01:15:50.606 --> 01:15:54.366
treatment? These really intensely sweet nutrition supplements.

1296
01:15:56.146 --> 01:15:56.786
Jacqueline

1297
01:15:59.826 --> 01:16:03.786
Di Meglio in the University of Florence, who's just graduated.

1298
01:16:03.846 --> 01:16:07.566
She's, I think, the only other dietician in the world I know with a taste PhD.

1299
01:16:08.186 --> 01:16:11.586
Asked patients a question

1300
01:16:11.726 --> 01:16:15.706
around which sensory characteristics should food products have

1301
01:16:15.786 --> 01:16:17.006
or asked a research question

1302
01:16:17.826 --> 01:16:20.266
to improve the eating experience of cancer patients.

1303
01:16:20.306 --> 01:16:22.446
And she gave people a forced choice

1304
01:16:23.486 --> 01:16:27.366
question around the ideal snack. What must the ideal snack

1305
01:16:27.406 --> 01:16:31.366
have and what must it not have? And the answer was that it must

1306
01:16:31.386 --> 01:16:33.626
be crunchy, it must be salty, it must be tasty.

1307
01:16:34.286 --> 01:16:37.886
It must not be milky, soft, sweet. So

1308
01:16:37.926 --> 01:16:40.406
these are common preferences we have.

1309
01:16:40.786 --> 01:16:44.486
In my study, ginger was a very

1310
01:16:44.566 --> 01:16:48.376
common effective thing that gave a taste sensation for people

1311
01:16:48.426 --> 01:16:51.886
who were feeling that it was blunted. It can also help with nausea.

1312
01:16:52.006 --> 01:16:54.746
Again, they're patient stories, but they're not to be discounted.

1313
01:16:54.906 --> 01:16:56.046
They're the best that we've got.

1314
01:16:57.746 --> 01:17:01.516
Okay. So what know-do gaps exist? We know that chemosensory

1315
01:17:01.586 --> 01:17:05.146
problems are common, and they do get reported when we ask, but we don't routinely

1316
01:17:05.286 --> 01:17:09.026
ask. We know taste is not taste. I'm going to talk about that more in a

1317
01:17:09.086 --> 01:17:09.786
minute,

1318
01:17:10.806 --> 01:17:13.966
and about words used to match the problem to the intervention or the

1319
01:17:14.006 --> 01:17:15.706
self-management technique we suggest.

1320
01:17:16.386 --> 01:17:19.916
Being forewarned is to be forearmed, but we don't routinely let patients know what

1321
01:17:19.926 --> 01:17:21.566
to expect. We're not doing very well, are we?

1322
01:17:22.226 --> 01:17:25.986
And some strategies are experienced by helpful by some patients, but we don't test

1323
01:17:26.026 --> 01:17:26.766
and evaluate them.

1324
01:17:28.026 --> 01:17:31.546
And so I want to introduce here Boltons Taxonomy of Taste.

1325
01:17:31.606 --> 01:17:33.726
Isn't that cute? I don't have a building named after me.

1326
01:17:33.966 --> 01:17:37.926
I named a taxonomy after me, and I had to do it myself,

1327
01:17:38.006 --> 01:17:38.666
but there it is.

1328
01:17:39.485 --> 01:17:42.286
And where this framework comes from, it's modeled off

1329
01:17:43.045 --> 01:17:46.126
physicians' work in the 1970s around the taste of pain.

1330
01:17:46.606 --> 01:17:50.066
Melzack and Jorgensen used patient descriptors to

1331
01:17:50.146 --> 01:17:54.066
help provide hints for the pathophysiological basis of the pain that

1332
01:17:54.086 --> 01:17:57.946
a patient was describing. Was it throbbing pain, tingling, stabbing,

1333
01:17:58.066 --> 01:18:01.626
burning pain? And so I used this kind of idea

1334
01:18:01.686 --> 01:18:05.546
by matching what patients were describing to give hints

1335
01:18:05.626 --> 01:18:08.886
about what it is we're actually dealing with here, because taste is not taste,

1336
01:18:08.946 --> 01:18:12.826
remember. So patients talk about food tasting like cardboard.

1337
01:18:14.106 --> 01:18:17.366
It's quite trite to say there isn't a basic taste of cardboard,

1338
01:18:18.466 --> 01:18:22.046
and I don't know how many of you have tasted and been on a cardboard diet.

1339
01:18:22.086 --> 01:18:25.456
But in all seriousness, what this is more about is about

1340
01:18:27.046 --> 01:18:28.246
mouth feel, about

1341
01:18:29.266 --> 01:18:29.706
texture,

1342
01:18:30.646 --> 01:18:33.006
about oral hygiene and oral dryness.

1343
01:18:33.426 --> 01:18:36.626
People talked about food tasting pins and needley.

1344
01:18:36.666 --> 01:18:38.326
This is about chemothesis that

1345
01:18:39.426 --> 01:18:43.366
Dr. Palmer talked about. And people have talked about food,

1346
01:18:43.566 --> 01:18:47.506
of course, lacking flavor, that muted sensation when you had the pegs on

1347
01:18:47.546 --> 01:18:51.486
your noses. And so I'm going to go on to show you how this work's

1348
01:18:51.526 --> 01:18:55.266
been bulked out to guide clinicians to then guide

1349
01:18:55.276 --> 01:18:58.546
patients, because we can get much more specific than some of the

1350
01:18:58.586 --> 01:19:02.376
generic things we tell patients to do, like drink out of a straw because it

1351
01:19:02.466 --> 01:19:03.886
bypasses the taste buds and

1352
01:19:04.726 --> 01:19:06.185
taste isn't as strong. That's not true.

1353
01:19:06.546 --> 01:19:06.746
I mean,

1354
01:19:07.826 --> 01:19:09.745
my scientist colleagues will tell us that.

1355
01:19:10.806 --> 01:19:14.726
Okay, so in the link down the bottom there, I know no one's from Australia,

1356
01:19:14.846 --> 01:19:16.246
but EvIQ

1357
01:19:17.106 --> 01:19:20.906
is a portal that's used in Australia to

1358
01:19:21.106 --> 01:19:25.066
stockpile clinical guidelines for cancer clinicians.

1359
01:19:25.646 --> 01:19:29.086
It includes things like safe administration of chemotherapy.

1360
01:19:29.966 --> 01:19:33.958
And it includesA guideline on

1361
01:19:33.998 --> 01:19:37.818
taste and smell dysfunction that, again, I developed 15

1362
01:19:37.858 --> 01:19:41.138
years ago. So I'm just going to talk to you a little bit about what's in here.

1363
01:19:41.178 --> 01:19:44.638
This is an excerpt in the patient education component of that

1364
01:19:44.738 --> 01:19:47.298
guideline, and like I said, it's freely available.

1365
01:19:48.458 --> 01:19:52.438
So we're using the patient descriptor that food tastes bland, or

1366
01:19:52.458 --> 01:19:55.318
it all tastes the same, or it tastes of nothing, or it lacks flavor.

1367
01:19:55.818 --> 01:19:59.798
And so that is likely to be an issue with taste sensitivity and

1368
01:19:59.878 --> 01:20:03.558
taste intensity. And then there's some definitions of what that

1369
01:20:03.638 --> 01:20:06.838
actually is, and then there's some information for patients and self-management

1370
01:20:06.898 --> 01:20:08.818
strategies. So for example,

1371
01:20:10.078 --> 01:20:13.558
and this is a trial and error bit, if food does taste too salty, try using

1372
01:20:15.018 --> 01:20:18.008
low-salt or no-salt alternatives to regular items.

1373
01:20:18.038 --> 01:20:22.018
If food tastes too sweet, try substituting breakfast cereals with no added

1374
01:20:22.118 --> 01:20:24.858
sugar, for example, oats instead of fruit-sweetened cereal.

1375
01:20:25.318 --> 01:20:29.278
And it sounds a bit basic and a bit boring, but in

1376
01:20:29.298 --> 01:20:32.518
the context of someone being really unwell and overwhelmed with a whole range of

1377
01:20:32.618 --> 01:20:33.468
symptoms and

1378
01:20:34.558 --> 01:20:38.478
treatment coming down the line, these are things that can be quite helpful to be

1379
01:20:38.518 --> 01:20:41.978
reminded of. But we don't follow up necessarily. How did that go?

1380
01:20:42.058 --> 01:20:44.258
How were the oats substituted with the breakfast cereal?

1381
01:20:44.288 --> 01:20:46.238
And capture that data and kind of

1382
01:20:47.738 --> 01:20:51.518
work out a greater sort of evidence base about what

1383
01:20:51.578 --> 01:20:54.878
is most effective. But it is very individually specific.

1384
01:20:55.118 --> 01:20:57.378
So again, not a criticism, just an observation.

1385
01:20:59.438 --> 01:21:02.178
So what then? These questions remain unanswered.

1386
01:21:02.478 --> 01:21:06.078
How should chemosensory function best be assessed in clinical practice?

1387
01:21:07.158 --> 01:21:10.418
Which interventions are most effective for treating these problems in the cancer

1388
01:21:10.518 --> 01:21:14.378
setting? When are the best opportunities to provide this education to patients,

1389
01:21:14.438 --> 01:21:18.188
and how do we best apply a virtuous cycle where clinical and

1390
01:21:18.238 --> 01:21:21.598
research data continuously guides practice?

1391
01:21:21.678 --> 01:21:25.438
And so what I mean by that is, in the EMR,

1392
01:21:25.578 --> 01:21:29.198
capturing the data, having MDT sessions where

1393
01:21:29.238 --> 01:21:31.318
clinicians and researchers are in there together.

1394
01:21:31.398 --> 01:21:33.778
We're kind of saying, "This is what happened with the patient.

1395
01:21:33.838 --> 01:21:36.458
This is what we tried instead. This is how we modified our practice.

1396
01:21:36.498 --> 01:21:37.758
This is what the result was."

1397
01:21:39.698 --> 01:21:42.138
I feel a clinical guideline coming on.

1398
01:21:43.718 --> 01:21:46.158
These are my hobby questions. You might have questions in the audience.

1399
01:21:46.238 --> 01:21:49.378
If anyone's interested in answering these questions, come and talk to us.

1400
01:21:49.858 --> 01:21:53.658
But from the three areas of my work life at the moment, to what extent do

1401
01:21:53.698 --> 01:21:57.467
taste and smell problems present uniquely or differently in women and

1402
01:21:57.498 --> 01:22:01.218
men? And then how can those differences be explained and guide

1403
01:22:01.498 --> 01:22:03.598
policy and practice or the non-differences?

1404
01:22:04.758 --> 01:22:07.618
GLP-1 inhibitors are increasingly

1405
01:22:08.358 --> 01:22:11.778
prescribed in the cancer context as well for both

1406
01:22:11.938 --> 01:22:15.678
prevention of cancer treatment and as a prehabilitative

1407
01:22:15.998 --> 01:22:19.798
component of cancer treatment, especially in cancers

1408
01:22:19.878 --> 01:22:23.378
where we know there's a link between clinically defined obesity and

1409
01:22:26.278 --> 01:22:30.198
cancer risk and poorer outcomes. And the one that I'm working on at the moment

1410
01:22:30.578 --> 01:22:34.258
in Australia is uterine cancers. I think it's called womb cancers here

1411
01:22:34.298 --> 01:22:35.158
in the US.

1412
01:22:36.358 --> 01:22:40.278
And medical oncologists in my institution

1413
01:22:40.418 --> 01:22:40.758
are

1414
01:22:41.758 --> 01:22:45.198
prescribing these drugs for cancer patients in that context.

1415
01:22:47.018 --> 01:22:50.998
How does the microbiome contribute to taste perception, and how does diet influence

1416
01:22:51.058 --> 01:22:54.498
this in the cancer context? And you might have other questions, and I think there

1417
01:22:54.558 --> 01:22:57.798
was two QR codes. So one at the start where you could pose your questions.

1418
01:22:57.858 --> 01:22:59.998
You can come up to the mic and ask questions there too.

1419
01:23:00.458 --> 01:23:03.038
But also, and we'll put this slide up right at the end again.

1420
01:23:03.838 --> 01:23:07.538
Valentina started with a slide that had a QR code on it, and really this session

1421
01:23:07.638 --> 01:23:11.458
has been our attempt, again, to bridge globally

1422
01:23:11.538 --> 01:23:15.038
these chemosensory and clinical oncology worlds.

1423
01:23:15.438 --> 01:23:19.338
And so if you have questions, we want to establish a new

1424
01:23:19.398 --> 01:23:23.018
community of practice, if you like, to investigate those, so you can upload your

1425
01:23:23.038 --> 01:23:25.038
questions and stay in touch via that route.

1426
01:23:26.658 --> 01:23:30.338
Okay, so there was lots of depressing stuff, but what can we do now in practice?

1427
01:23:31.258 --> 01:23:34.098
Talk about taste to your patients.

1428
01:23:34.518 --> 01:23:37.918
Make better use of that routine data if there's dashboards and things like that.

1429
01:23:38.318 --> 01:23:41.618
Valentina talked about incorporating it into Epic, into the EMR.

1430
01:23:42.598 --> 01:23:45.018
Work with patients and individuals. What's worked for you?

1431
01:23:45.098 --> 01:23:47.738
What can you still enjoy? What should we modify?

1432
01:23:47.958 --> 01:23:49.178
And revisit that.

1433
01:23:50.038 --> 01:23:53.918
Do not provide false hope. As a clinician, it's very tempting to want to give

1434
01:23:53.937 --> 01:23:56.678
all the answers. Sometimes it's okay to say we don't know. We don't know.

1435
01:23:56.738 --> 01:24:00.418
This is still under investigation, but we want to work with you as a patient to

1436
01:24:00.478 --> 01:24:03.378
understand what works best for you, and that might also help other people.

1437
01:24:04.098 --> 01:24:06.158
And promote the importance of oral care.

1438
01:24:08.238 --> 01:24:11.758
Where to next? We're going to collate and progress these additional questions.

1439
01:24:11.818 --> 01:24:15.738
Like we said, I'd recommend applying a learning health system approach

